The second single released in advance of the album Pompeii (2022).



In a press release, Le Bon describes the background of “Moderation” as

“a nod to the daily dilemma of trying to curb inherited and novel habits, when you want to eat the moon, and an essay written by the architect Lina Bo Bardi in 1958 that continues to kick hard.”

body.plain:
The second single released in advance of the album Pompeii (2022).



In a press release, Le Bon describes the background of “Moderation” as

“a nod to the daily dilemma of trying to curb inherited and novel habits, when you want to eat the moon, and an essay written by the architect Lina Bo Bardi in 1958 that continues to kick hard.”

annotations: Picture the party where you’re standing on a modern age

Cate paints this song as an homage to Italian-born Brazilian architect Lina Bo Bardi. Le Bon draws from her essay “The Moon” (1958), which chastises scientific progress of conquering the moon, as she believes the conquering of the moon overlooked important material and humanitarian needs of the earth. In the Apple Music track-by-track of this album, Le Bon explains:

All these incremental decisions that man has made that have led to climate disaster and people trying to get to the moon, but completely disregarding that we’ve got a housing crisis, and all these things that don’t really make sense. We’ve lost the ability to account for what matters, and it will ultimately be the demise of man. We know all this, and yet we still crave the things that are feeding into this.”

In this line, she is describing the moon landing, “standing on the modern age”.
“I can’t stand it”, according to the official lyrics posted via Apple Music, but clearly “I can’t have it” in the performance.
“Mother of Pearl” – a song from Roxy Music’s Stranded (1973). Cate Le Bon’s recent albums share some similarities with Roxy Music’s later albums, particularly Avalon (1982).

description.plain:
In a press release, Cate states that

‘Remembering Me’ is a neurotic diary entry that questions notions of legacy and warped sentimentalism in the desperate need to self mythologise.

In “Remembering Me”, Cate Le Bon highlights the importance of living intentionally, rather than letting potential legacy dictate our choices. People desire to only be remembered for their highs, and tend to sanitize their pasts. This song showcases the need to live in the present, and not tear ourselves down for past choices, artistic or personal. Her mythologized life is presented in a series of hyperboles, and she strips these comparisons back in the choruses to reveal her depressed, lonely self.

It’s about this idea that love is a universal word that everyone recognizes and thinks has a very specific meaning—but it doesn’t. The spectrum of how this word is viewed is immense. It has lots and lots of different meanings depending on who’s using it.

A reference to Shakespeare.
“Love is not love
Which alters when it alteration finds,
Or bends with the remover to remove”
from Sonnet 116
